<br>
I heard something on The Splendid Table yesterday about research that has shown that the weather in New England at the time of the hysteria was such to facilitate the growth of a fungus called ergot on the rye crops.  Ergot contains the chemical basis of LSD.  I had never heard this before.  <br>
Interesting although unrelated, ergot was also used in early medicine: in small doses to speed up contractions during childbirth, in larger doses to prevent an unwanted pregnancy.<br>
<br>
-Simone <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mightyk>MightyK</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 243<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/5/03 9:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=200.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Salem Witch Trials</span><hr size=1> Mass hysteria, combined with the bad rye which I had read about a few years ago. Hmm, might be a lot more then a few years now. And a fanatical belief system which supported that type of behavior. <br>
<br>
On a side note, during my grandfather's search of our geneology, he discovered we had two two accused and one condemned witch in our family. I don't remember the story of the younger woman, I guess it wasn't too interesting - it was also 15 or so years ago that he told us about this. And the other was an older woman from a smaller town near Salem. She was actually condemned, but when it came time for her to die, her towns folk went to Salem and rescued her and then refused to hand her back over. At least I believe that is how it went. <br>
<br>
Kim <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=luvthatdyl>LuvThatDyl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 153<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/5/03 2:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=200.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Salem Witch Trials</span><hr size=1> I had heard the theory about the ergot too, and I think it is a very valid one.  I believe that when you have a phenomena among a group that doesn't have the scientific knowledge to properly analyze it, and then you combine it with over the top religious beliefs, then you've got a witch craze.  There was also something in one of the Shermer books I read about feeding into a cycle, but I'm having a brain fart on the details right now.  Since DBC obviously isn't pregnant right now, I'm sure his brain is functioning much better than mine, and he can clarify that for me.  <br>
<br>
I had read the book that was an adaptation of the miniseries that recently came out about the witch trials, and it delved into the religious beliefs of these people.  Their religious beliefs were pretty warped IMO, and I think it had a role to play.  These people couldn't even laugh and have a good time without thinking they were sinning against God.  I think religion definitely played into this.  I don't mean that as a knock on religion in general, but more about the extreme beliefs of the Puritans.<br>
<br>
